\begin_body

\begin_layout Title
Do workers discriminate against their out-group employers? Evidence from
 an online labor market
\end_layout

\begin_layout Abstract
A large body of literature in economics has demonstrated that prejudice
 or bias of the majority group towards members of an out-group identity
 – whether it be racial, religious, ethnic or gender in origin – is widespread
 in labor markets.
 Such biases often lead to discrimination when, all else same, a less-favorable
 treatment is systematically meted out to the 
\change_deleted 253428369 1560299570
out-
\change_inserted 253428369 1560299573
 subordinate 
\change_unchanged
group relative to the 
\change_deleted 2090806916 1560258633
majority
\change_unchanged
 
\change_deleted 253428369 1560299483
in-
\change_inserted 253428369 1560299486
 dominant 
\change_unchanged
group
\change_inserted 2090806916 1560258645

