\begin_layout Standard
We make a simplifying assumption that the workers of type 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 are homogeneous given a treatment i.e.
 they will make the same effort choice in a given treatment.
 We later relax this assumption to account for heterogeneity in effort within
 a treatment.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Piece Rate Treatments
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the piece rate treatments, each worker works on a task at a given piece
 rate.
 We assign four different piece rates between 0 and 10 cents.
 In the first treatment, workers are paid no piece rate.
 In the next three treatments, 
\change_inserted 2090806916 1560276686
the 
\change_unchanged
piece rates are 3, 6 and 9 cents per unit of effort.
 From the M-Turk standards, this variation in piece rates is substantial
 and is likely to elicit significant change in effort.
 The piece rates are earned on top of $1 fixed participation fee.
 These four treatments differ only in the piece rates, everything else remains
 exactly the same.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
These piece rates provide evidence on the responsiveness of effort to incentives
 for our particular task and hence
\change_inserted 2090806916 1560276957
,
\change_unchanged
 allow us to estimate the baseline parameters (
\begin_inset Formula $s_{i},$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

) which will be used to estimate other behavioral parameters.
 Formally, in the piece rate treatments, worker 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 observes the piece rate 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 and then chooses effort 
\begin_inset Formula $e_{ij}$
\end_inset

 by maximizing 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:utility"

\end_inset

.
 There is no employer 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

 in these treatments which implies that for any worker 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha_{ij}=0$
\end_inset

 and there is no gift from the employer implying 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbbm{1}_{Gift}=0$
\end_inset

.
 The equilibrium efforts 
\begin_inset Formula $e_{i}^{\star}$
\end_inset

 in these treatments is thus given as; 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
e_{i}^{\star}=c'^{-1}\left(s_{i}+p\right)\text{ for }i\in\left\{ B,W\right\} \text{ and \ensuremath{p\in\{0,3,6,9\}}}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For each 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

, the solution of effort has one behavioral unknown (
\begin_inset Formula $s_{i}$
\end_inset

), and two unknowns from the cost function (
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

).
 To back out these parameters
\change_inserted 2090806916 1560277102
,
\change_unchanged
 we use effort corresponding to three different piece rates which gives
 us three equations to identify these three parameters.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Altruism Treatments
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the altruism treatments, each worker is matched to an employer (truthfully)
 and 
\change_inserted 2090806916 1560277242
he
\change_inserted 253428369 1560299703
/she
\change_inserted 2090806916 1560277242
 
\change_unchanged
observes the (true) value of the effort to the matched employer.
 Each employer earns 1 cent for every 100 points scored by the matched worker.
 We set the piece rate to 0.
 There are three treatments under altruism treatments.
 In the first treatment (altruism baseline) a worker does not observe the
 identity of the matched employer.
 In the 'altruism black' and 'altruism white' treatment the matched employer
 is black and white
\change_inserted 2090806916 1560277337
,
\change_unchanged
 respectively.
 Note that 
