\begin_layout Section
Planned Analysis
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For the analysis of data, we envision three main sections.
 In the first section, we will describe the collected data from M-Turkers
 including data cleaning and balance checks on the demographic data across
 treatments.
 The second section will present the treatment effects for all the ten treatment
s including the heterogeneity of the treatment effects.
 In the third section, we will estimate our structural model and get the
 estimates of the behavioral parameters.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Data Cleaning and Summary Statistics
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To prepare data for the analysis, we will apply some cleaning to the collected
 data.
 Specifically, we will apply
\change_inserted 2090806916 1560280299
 the
\change_unchanged
 following restrictions to the collected data: 1) we will only analyze the
 data of M-Turkers who complete the experiment i.e.
 we will not analyze the data of participants who drop out before working
 on the task, 2) we will drop all the observation that score above 4,000
 points since this is physically impossible in 10 minutes and these users
 would have used some automated script to score these points or they may
 have experienced some technical problem, 3) we will drop all the observations
 with zero points as this may reflect some malfunction or technical problem
 in points recording
\change_inserted 2090806916 1560280364
 
\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\change_inserted 2090806916 1560280374
no possibility of extensive margin?
\change_inserted 253428369 1560306569
 No.
 Now that we are making people to spend 10 minutes on the page, it seems
 very weird that a person will not even score a single point.
 DellaVigna and Pope dropped these observations too.
 
\change_unchanged

\end_layout

\end_inset


\change_unchanged
, 4) we will drop data of users who stop the task and login again as these
 people may be trying to game the experiment by trying to be assigned to
 most rewarding treatment.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We are using blocked randomization design to assign subjects to treatments,
 so our treatments should be balanced on the blocked variables (gender,
 age, education, income, most-lived US state, and party affiliation).
 Nevertheless, we will present plots to test whether we get balanced treatments
 on these covariates.
 We will use Kolmogorov–Smirnov test to compare the distribution of demographics
 in these treatments.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We will present the summary statistics on the information collected from
 the M-Turkers to assess the representativeness of our sample as compared
 to US population.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Treatment Effects
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We will first present a table of average efforts (points scored) along with
 standard errors for each of the ten treatments.
 This table will give a sense of how the effort varies from one treatment
 to another.
 We will also plot the mean and standard deviation to document the variance
 of effort across treatments.
 This will capture in a snapshot the motivation of workers regarding the
 impact of different behavioral levers in our setting.
 For example, do the workers respond to incentives? Are the workers altruistic
 towards their employers? Do they exhibit any reciprocity? Do the race of
 the employer effects worker's performance?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The data will provide us with some qualitative answers on the questions
 above by comparing the effort choices in the behavioral treatment to the
 relevant control treatment.
 For example, the comparison between `Altruism - Baseline' and `Piece Rate
 - 0 cents' will answer whether workers are altruistic towards their employers.
 Similarly comparison of effort choices in `Altruism - Baseline' and `Reciprocit
y - Baseline' will suggest evidence of reciprocity towards the employer,
 if any.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The main theme of this paper is to test the difference in motivation towards
 black and white employers.
 We will use data from `Altruism - Black' and `Altruism - White' to test
 whether workers are more or less altruistic towards black versus white
 employers
\change_inserted 2090806916 1560280542
 
\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\change_inserted 2090806916 1560280598
at some point, we need to mention clearly that is project is all about understan
ding differential effort of white workers towards black and white employer?
\change_unchanged

\end_layout

\end_inset


\change_unchanged
.
 Similarly, comparison of `Reciprocity - Black' and `Reciprocity - White'
 will reveal any differential reciprocal preferences towards blacks versus
 white employers.
 
\change_inserted 253428369 1560299179
Assuming normality and equal variance of distributions for each treatment,
 we may employ t-test to test for the differences in average effort.
 
\change_unchanged

\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Comparisons between `Piece Rate - 0 cents', `Piece Rate - 3 cents', `Piece
 Rate - 6 cents' and `Piece Rate - 9 cents' will answer whether worker's
 effort increase with increase in the incentive for work.
 These piece rate treatments will help us calculate the elasticity of effort
 (as explained below).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We will also compare the cumulative distribution of effort (points scored)
 across these treatments to get the better understanding of how the effort
 choices change in each of these treatments.
 As another piece of our reduced form analysis, we will analyze the evolution
 of effort over the 10-mintues period across all these treatments.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Having compared the overall effort choices to examine the treatment effects,
 we can compare the treatment effects for different groups - males versus
 females, high income versus low income, highly educated versus less educated,
 blue states versus red states, and young versus old.
 Since we used the blocked randomization on these covariates to assign treatment
s, we can make these comparisons with high enough power.
 
\change_inserted 253428369 1560310614

\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\change_inserted 253428369 1560311872
Since our race revelation mechanism is very subtle, it is possible that
 the race of the employer may not become salient to the workers.
 This can happen because a worker fails to pay attention to the video or
 he/she may have low to non-existent implicit bias towards the opposite
 race.
 To partially address this concern, we will elicit incentivized beliefs
 of workers about the matched employer after they have finished working
 on the task.
 Each worker will be incentivized to make a guess about the demographics
 of the matched employer (gender, age, race, education, income).
 We will analyze the heterogeneity in treatment effects based on whether
 workers correctly guessed the race of the employer.
 
\begin_inset Note Note
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\change_inserted 253428369 1560311673
How else can we use these belief data?
\change_unchanged

\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\change_inserted 253428369 1560312802
We may also use the data on beliefs to understand more about the beliefs
 of white workers about the black employers relative to the white employers.
 For example, it will be interesting to see whether workers believe that
 black employers are poor relative to white employers and does this play
 a part in explaining their effort choices? Note that even though these
 beliefs may cause the differential effort for black versus white employers,
 these effort choices are still purely driven by the social preferences
 of workers.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Estimation of Structural Model
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We designed our experiment with the structural model given in Section 2.
 The advantage of designing field experiments on the basis of model of behavior
 is that it allows researchers to estimate the nuisance parameters in the
 environment that is relevant to the decision making 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
citep{DellaVigna2017}
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 Because of the simplicity of our task, there are only three nuisance parameters
 that we need to estimate.
 We will thus use data from the piece rate treatments to identify these
 parameters.
 Once we have the estimate of these nuisance parameters, we can estimate
 behavioral parameters using data from the social preference treatments.
 We closely follow the estimation procedure in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Dellavigna2018"

\end_inset

 to estimate our model.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We will first use minimum distance estimation method to estimate these parameter
s.
 In the minimum distance estimation one identifies the set of moments in
 data (average effort) and then find the set of model parameters that minimizes
 the distance between the empirical moments and the theory-predicted moments.
 To estimate nuisance parameters, we will use data from the piece rate treatment
s.
 Specifically, we will use the average effort corresponding to three piece
 rates (0 cents, 3 cents and 9 cents), to estimate 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\gamma}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{s}$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{k}$
\end_inset

.
 Once these parameters are estimated, we will use average effort corresponding
 to altruism treatment to estimate behavioral parameter 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

.
 Having estimated nuisance parameters and baseline altruism parameter, we
 will use average effort in `Altruism - Black' and `Altruism - White' to
 estimate 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha_{Black}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha_{White}$
\end_inset

 respectively.
 Similarly, to calculate baseline reciprocity parameter 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho$
\end_inset

, we will use average effort from `Rec
\change_inserted 2090806916 1560280778
i
\change_unchanged
procity - Baseline' treatment while taking the nuisance and altruism parameters
 as given.
 Finally, we will estimate 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho_{Black}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho_{White}$
\end_inset

 using average effort in `Reciprocity - Black' and `Reci
\change_deleted 2090806916 1560280786
r
\change_unchanged
p
\change_inserted 2090806916 1560280788
r
\change_unchanged
ocity - White' respectively, taking other parameters as given.
 We will derive confidence interval for these parameters using a bootstrap
 procedure.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The minimum distance estimator just relies on the moment and hence
\change_inserted 2090806916 1560280816
,
\change_unchanged
 does not use all the variation in the data.
 There are methods such as maximum likelihood and non-linear least squares
 that can be used to estimate these parameters using all the variation in
 the data.
 We will use non-linear least square method to estimate these parameters
 allowing for the heterogeneous cost of effort.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As explained in section 2, we will use both the power and the exponential
 cost function to estimate these parameters.
 
\change_inserted 253428369 1560310526

\end_layout

